<p>Experimentation drives change.  It is a means to stimulate imagination and increase awareness of the "weak signals" of impending change.  It allows us to see ourselves and the enemy differently - shifting from a reactive to a proactive stance that allows us to recognize and influence change before "strong signals" force us to adapt on others' terms.</p>
<p>U.S. Army Training and Doctrine Command (TRADOC) Battle Labs reside in each Center of Excellence (CoE), and are equipped with a capacity and infrastructure that enables each to modernize its warfighting function.  By integrating the warfighting functions, experimentation conducted at these labs enables ARCIC to understand interactions between warfighting functions, among our sister services, and our multinational partners. This identifies interdependencies, gaps, and redundancies, allowing the Army to shape a holistic and coherent transition from the current force to the future force.</p>
<p class="BubbleTitleSection">WHAT IS EXPERIMENTATION?</p>
<p>First, it's important to distinguish an experiment and an evaluation.  Experiments immerse Soldiers into a future Joint Operating Environment. It positions them against a thinking, adaptive enemy in order to learn and mitigate risk.  Evaluations connect Soldiers to mature network capabilities in order to determine whether they perform as needed, conform to the network architecture, and are interoperable with existing systems.  Other differences include: concepts versus doctrine; transitioning the force versus developing the future force; mid-term versus near-term; technology readiness levels 3-6 versus levels 7-8.</p>
